,Recommended,209230,13461351,"Posted: 19 December, 2014",all,Little Puffski,"If you enjoy this type of games, you can't go wrong with this one. Unlike the terrible Sherlock Holmes: Mystery of Persian Carpet, this game is vastly improved in every way. Story is without a doubt the weakest link, but would you really expect a respectful interpretation of the original story in hidden objects game? It's fine and if you accept it for what it is, it's really not that bad, just think of it as a non-canon supernatural tour through the Baskerville manor.Gameplay is great, difficulty is quite low, which is fine by me, I don't want to be stuck for too long on strange puzzles or impossible to see objects. Achievements are nice as well, motivates you to do them, since they're not too hard. Overall I've thoroughly enjoyed playing it."
76561198042771716,Recommended,209230,4877335,"Posted: 3 August, 2012",all,SwimmingRock,"If you're trying to learn about Sherlock Holmes, this is the wrong place to start. It takes the basic plot of the novel (demonic dog targets family) and then goes batshit crazy with it. Fortunately, they do it in such a fun way that I don't think it detracts from the game at all.It's a very good-looking point-and-click game with some pretty good puzzles and very good pacing. Sure, there are too many Hidden Objects puzzles, but those are so easy and short that I was never annoyed by it. Puzzles vary in difficulty and there are a few types of puzzles that make a second appearance, but there's still a lot of variation.The music is a bit overly dramatic, but certainly not bad. Not memorable either, though. Controls and the map work really well and the whole thing is well executed, although the dialogue and cinematics are mediocre.Still, all the parts you actually play are a lot of fun, provided you don't worry about canon or taking things too seriously."
